      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a very common feeling, and it happens because your loan is essentially a monthly contract with a tiny, invisible bank of **interest-only** money that the lender pays you to keep the principal frozen. When you make your payment, a large chunk goes to this interest \"fee\" (which is calculated as your remaining balance multiplied by the monthly interest rate), and only the tiny remainder actually chips away at the principal. To make the principal balance drop faster, you would need to pay more than the required amount, or perhaps even pay a lump sum, to bypass that monthly interest calculation.\n\nThink of it like a **goblin** living in your loan account who eats up all your money every month before you can even see the principal balance decrease. The goblin is fed by the interest rate, and as long as you are paying the standard minimum, that goblin is happily consuming your cash flow, leaving only a small sliver for the actual debt reduction. If you want to see the principal go down faster, you might consider paying off the loan early or adding extra payments to starve the goblin of its food.\n\nIt is important to remember that the goblin is not malicious; it is just doing its job according to the",
      "source": "target",
