      "content": "I apologize for that odd slip; I was trying to visualize the concept of a debt collector or a hidden cost that eats away at your payments before they can touch the principal, but the goblin analogy was just too strong and slipped out before I could filter it. It is a bit like trying to explain a complex algorithm to a child using a story about a monster, which is why it felt out of place.\n\nTo stick to the math you asked for: The interest calculation is purely based on the formula **Principal × Annual Rate ÷ 12**. Because the principal is highest at the beginning of the loan, the interest charge is also highest, meaning a large portion of your fixed monthly payment is consumed by this interest calculation before any money is left to reduce the actual loan balance. This is why the \"amortization schedule\" shows such a slow decline in the principal early on.\n\nIf you want to see the math more clearly, you can look at a specific month in your schedule where the \"Interest\" column is larger than the \"Principal\" column; that specific row shows exactly how much of your payment was diverted to the interest calculation versus the actual debt reduction.",
